<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="part1">
  <title>Propositions and Connectives</title>

  <p>
    A proposition is a statement that is either true or false, but not both.
    Questions below test whether a sentence qualifies as a proposition.
  </p>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      Determine whether each of the following is a proposition. If it is, state whether it is true or false.

      <ol type="a">
        <li>The Eiffel Tower is in Paris.</li>
        <li>Is it raining?</li>
        <li><m>5 + 3 = 9</m></li>
        <li>Close the door.</li>
      </ol>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      (a) Proposition, True  
      (b) Not a proposition  
      (c) Proposition, False  
      (d) Not a proposition
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      Let <m>p</m>: "It is raining", and <m>q</m>: "I will take an umbrella".

      Translate the following statements into symbolic logic.
    </statement>

    <solution>
      (a) <m>p \rightarrow q</m><br/>
      (b) <m>\neg p \land \neg q</m><br/>
      (c) <m>p \lor q</m>
    </solution>
  </exercise>
</section>